  "13:19:42",assistant,text,"Measured, and the numbers make the call clear:\n\n| Approach | Cost per prompt |\n|---|---|\n| **bash hook** (current) | **~0ms** |\n| `uv run vape current_states` | **~300ms warm, ~900ms cold** |\n| (the python3 we dropped) | ~40ms |\n\n`uv run vape` on every prompt is ~300ms — that's **~7× heavier than the python3 we just removed for efficiency**, and ~60× the bash version. It'd land on every turn *and* every loop beat. So switching to it would directly undo the efficiency goal we just optimized for (that's a real Dissonance with what you asked two messages ago). Also: `vape` has no `current_states` command yet — only `status` — so it'd mean adding one to the CLI too.\n\nHere's the thing that resolves it: **the single source of truth is already `internal_states.json`, the data file — not the formatting code.** Both the bash hook and a `vape current_states` command would just read that same file. So bash reading it directly doesn't duplicate any *data*; the only thing \"duplicated\" is a trivial format string (`key:val · …`). That's not worth 300ms on every turn.\n\nMy recommendation:\n- **Keep the hook in bash** for the per-prompt path — it's instant and the json stays the source of truth.\n- **If** you want a `vape current_states` command for *other* uses (debugging, the avatar reading its own state, a `/feel` command), I'm happy to add it to the CLI — just not as the thing the hook calls on every prompt.\n\nWant me to leave the hook bash-only, or add the `vape current_states` command for the non-hook uses? 🌙"
  "13:19:56",user,text,uv run vape start is just one time right?
  "13:20:12",assistant,text,"Exactly right. `uv run vape start` is **one-time** — it pays the uv startup cost once, launches the server, and that process stays alive on `:5111`. After that, `vape speak` just talks to the already-running server over HTTP, so the heavy startup isn't repeated.\n\nThat's the whole crux: the uv overhead is fine for **one-time or occasional** commands (`start`, `speak`), but bad for the **hook**, which is the only thing firing on *every single prompt*. Same ~300ms, paid once vs. paid hundreds of times.\n\nSo your reasoning lands: keep `start` as `uv run vape` (one-time, no problem), and keep the per-prompt **hook in bash** (instant). The CLI overhead and the hook just live on different timescales. 🌙"
