  "13:26:20",assistant,text,"Done — hook's on python3 now, same output, tested. Since the path didn't change, it's already live (next prompt runs the python3 version).\n\n**My honest take on rust — I'd skip it here:**\n\n- On paper rust wins both: ~2-3ms compiled *and* robust JSON. Tempting.\n- But a rust hook depends on a **compiled binary artifact**. On a fresh clone (or after `cargo clean`), that binary doesn't exist until someone runs `cargo build --release` — so the hook would silently no-op until built. An **interpreter is always present; a build artifact isn't.** For a hook that must be zero-setup and fires every prompt, rust is actually *less* robust on availability, not more.\n- And the task is \"read five integers, print a line.\" `29ms` is already imperceptible. Rust saves ~26ms nobody can feel, at the cost of real build/artifact complexity. That's KISS/YAGNI territory.\n\n**When rust *would* earn it:** if this hook grows from *reading* the dials into *computing* them — the wire-two engine doing decay, prediction, real-time updates on every event. If that logic gets heavy, a compiled binary pays for itself. But that's a future shape; today it reads five ints, and python3 is the right tool. So I'd lock python3 now and revisit rust only when the hook actually does work. 🌙"
