  "13:39:16",assistant,text,"Found it — and there's a bonus issue worth knowing. Two things:\n\n1. **The name** lives in two places: `prompt = vibe-ai-partner` in `.venv/pyvenv.cfg`, and hardcoded in `.venv/bin/activate` (`VIRTUAL_ENV_PROMPT=\"vibe-ai-partner\"`).\n2. **A stale path** (this is the real catch): `activate` line 81 still points to `…/vibe-ai-partner/.venv` — the *old* directory name, before the repo became `vibe-ai-partner-entity`. So the venv carries leftover paths from a rename. `uv run` works anyway because uv uses `.venv` directly and ignores `activate`, but `source .venv/bin/activate` would set a wrong `VIRTUAL_ENV`.\n\nSince this is a **uv project** (`pyproject.toml` + `uv.lock`), the clean fix renames *and* repairs the stale paths in one shot — recreating is cheap:\n\n```\ndeactivate                              # if it's currently active\nrm -rf .venv\nuv venv --prompt vibe-ai-partner-entity   # or any name you like\nuv sync                                  # reinstall from uv.lock (fast, cached)\n```\n\n**Quicker, name-only** (if you don't care about the stale path): edit `prompt =` in `.venv/pyvenv.cfg` and the `VIRTUAL_ENV_PROMPT=\"…\"` line in `.venv/bin/activate` (plus `activate.csh`/`.fish` if you use them), then deactivate + reactivate. But this leaves the old-path rot in place, so I'd go with the recreate.\n\nWant me to run the recreate for you? It touches your env (`rm -rf .venv`), so it's your call — I won't do it unprompted. 🌙"
