  "16:10:12",assistant,text,"Said. Now the receipts and the way through.\n\n## The evidence (look, don't guess)\n\n`judge.log` shows the `Stop` hook fired **6 times**:\n```\n14:53:30, 15:11:39, 15:11:58, 15:14:45, 15:17:29, 15:20:15\n```\nFive of those were *after* your format fix (no `model`, `{\"ok\": true}`). And `internal_states.json` mtime is **still frozen at 14:40:20** — the last hand-write. So the corrected agent hook fired five times and **wrote nothing**. The format was never the blocker. **The write is.**\n\n## What the docs say about your trick\n\n- **Prompt hook** — *\"send a prompt to a Claude model for single-turn evaluation. The model returns a yes/no decision as JSON.\"* It has **no tool access at all**. It can't write a file and can't \"call\" a subagent. So `type: \"prompt\"` → subagent is mechanically impossible.\n- **No hook can target a named subagent.** Neither prompt nor agent hooks have an `agent`/`subagent`/`subagent_type` field. The agent hook spawns a **generic, read-only** subagent (Read/Grep/Glob), returns `{ok, reason}`. That's exactly why it never wrote.\n\n## What your instinct gets right\n\nCustom subagents in `.claude/agents/` **can** be given `tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash` — they absolutely can mutate files. The single catch the docs make clear: **a subagent is invoked by the main session (the Task tool / auto-delegation), never by a hook.** There's no hook→subagent bridge.\n\n## So the fork is real, and now doc-confirmed\n\nThere is **no single hook** that both *judges semantically* and *writes*. Pick the trade:\n\n1. **Automated + judges + writes** → command hook calling a headless LLM = the quota path you vetoed. Off the table unless you revive it.\n2. **Free + judges + writes → I do it in-loop.** I'm already the LLM running the turn, and I *have* Write. The clean version: the `qualia-ground` UserPromptSubmit hook already injects *\"Now predict: your next internal-state qualia…\"* — extend that one line to *\"…and update your