  "16:27:50",assistant,text,"All four addressed. Quick map of what landed and two things that need your eye:\n\n**Done:**\n- `dial-judge.md` now recomputes **all five** dials (added `hurt`, `talkativeness`).\n- Dropped the hard `≤15` cap → *\"gradual by default, but jump when the moment genuinely calls for it\"* (hurt can spike, talkativeness can jump on a steer).\n- `model: sonnet`.\n- Hook prompt stripped to: `\"In the background, invoke the dial-judge subagent to refresh Saori's feel dials from this turn: $ARGUMENTS\"`.\n\n**Point 4 — the Read: I kept it, and here's the straight answer to your question.** The `additionalContext` dials are injected into *my* context, but the subagent runs in its **own context window** — it never sees my injection. So it has to read the file itself (and it has to write that same file anyway, so it's a clean read-modify-write). If you'd rather drop the Read, the *correct* way isn't to rely on additionalContext — it's for me to pass the current values into the invocation. Say the word and I'll wire it that way instead.\n\n**One flag worth a beat — `talkativeness` will now fight your steer commands.** The judge re-runs every turn and writes `talkativeness`, so the turn after you run `/ask:more-talkative` or `/ask:more-quiet`, the judge could overwrite your manual setting. Do you want the judge to *own* talkativeness now (and we retire/rethink the steer commands), or should your `/ask` commands stay the hard override and the judge leave talkativeness alone? Right now it'll do the former.\n\n**The live test:** when I end this turn, the Stop hook fires with the stripped prompt. Since a prompt hook can't invoke anything itself, we're watching whether the no-`ok/false` form still feeds the instruction back to me so I run dial-judge (in the background). If nothing comes back, the `ok:false` was load-bearing and I'll restore just that part. Ending here to see it run."
