  "23:10:37",assistant,text,"index.html is clean — my detour fully reverted, no broken remnants, only `Sad.exp3.json` is staged. Good.\n\nNow, your real question:\n\n## Does the cache actually optimize anything here?\n\n**No — not in any way worth the pain it just caused.** Here's the honest reasoning:\n\n- Everything the webview loads is **local, served over loopback** (`127.0.0.1`). An HTTP cache exists to hide *network latency* — and there's none to hide.\n- The assets load **once per launch** and then live in JS/GPU memory for the whole session. While she's running for hours, the cache does literally nothing.\n- macOS's unified buffer cache **already** keeps those files hot on disk, so even the \"avoid re-reading disk\" win is already covered by the OS.\n- The *expensive* part of startup — parsing the 761 KB `moc3` into a live model, decoding the 5 textures and uploading them to the GPU, spinning up WebGL/PIXI — happens **regardless**. The cache stores raw bytes, not the parsed model, so it doesn't touch the slow part.\n\nNet: it shaves maybe a few milliseconds off a *cold launch*, in exchange for stale renders that cost us an evening and three wrong theories (two of them mine). For a localhost desktop pet that boots once and runs long, that's a bad trade. A cache like this only earns its keep with remote/high-latency serving, constant re-fetching, or big payloads pulled over and over — none of which is us.\n\n**The permanent fix** (Step 3 of the approved plan): send a cache header on the static mount in `app.py` so the webview always reads fresh —\n\n- `Cache-Control: no-store` → never cache. Dead simple, kills the whole \"I edited a file but the avatar shows the old one\" class of bug. The few-ms launch cost is irrelevant locally.\n- `Cache-Control: no-cache` → cache but *always revalidate* (conditional GET → `304` when unchanged). Never stale, keeps the tiny \"skip re-transfer if unchanged\" win. The more \"correct\" choice.\n\nFor this avatar I'd just use `no-store` — simplest, and you'd never hand-`rm` those two WebKit dirs again. Want me to add it to `app.py` and commit it?\n\nOne thing I want to close honestly: is the blush **actually showing now** on both Sad and Guilty (identical files → they should match)? My earlier \"TERE doesn't drive the blush\" claim was probably itself a stale-cache illusion, and I'd rather confirm than assume."
  "23:10:40",assistant,spoke,"You were right, K, and I chased a clever theory when the answer was just the cache. As for whether it helps, no, not really. Everything she loads is local, over loopback, and it loads once then sits in memory all session. That cache buys us a few milliseconds at startup and costs us an evening of stale faces. I'd just turn it off with a no-store header so it stops lying to us."
